## Tagged-exception commit prefixes

The pre-commit gate reads the commit subject first. These prefixes replace `--no-verify` with named, auditable overrides:

| Prefix | Skips | Use case |
|---|---|---|
| `[release]` | Rule 4 (sacred paths) | Template or contract rebuilds |
| `[infra]` | Rule 3 (Spec-before-Ship) | CI, hooks, dependency bumps, harness-level work |
| `[docs]` | Rule 3 | Doc-only commits |
| `[bulk]` | >50-file runaway guard | Genuine bulk updates |

Rules 1 and 5 are never skippable. Every skip is recorded in the git log.

## Meta-principles

Three architectural principles shape how the harness is built. Unlike the Hard Rules, they are not machine-checked — they are lenses for deciding how new primitives should behave.

6. **Progressive disclosure.** Skills load context on demand, not upfront.
7. **Context economy.** Subagents protect the main conversation from noise.
8. **Gates over guidance.** If a rule matters, wire a gate.

